  "prompt": "What is the stall speed and AOA of an f-14 with wings fully swept back?",
  "response": "The McDonnell Douglas F-14 Tomcat is a supersonic, twin-engine, two-seat fighter aircraft known for its variable-sweep wings, which can be adjusted to optimize performance at various speeds and flight conditions. When the wings are fully swept back, the aerodynamic characteristics of the aircraft change significantly, affecting both the stall speed and the angle of attack (AOA).\n\n### **Stall Speed**\n\n- **Fully Swept Wings:** When the F-14's wings are fully swept back (approximately 68 degrees), the **stall speed increases** compared to the fully unswept position. In this configuration, the effective wing area contributing to lift at low speeds is reduced, necessitating a higher speed to achieve the necessary lift to prevent a stall.\n  \n  - **Approximate Stall Speed:** **200 knots indicated airspeed (KIAS)**\n\n### **Angle of Attack (AOA) at Stall**\n\n- **Fully Swept Wings:** With the wings fully swept, the aircraft requires a higher angle of attack to generate the necessary lift as the wing's ability to produce lift at low speeds diminishes. The increased sweep leads to a delay in stall onset but requires the nose to be pitched higher when approaching stall conditions.\n\n  - **Approximate AOA at Stall:** **23 degrees**\n\n### **Summary**\n\n- **Stall Speed:** ~200 KIAS\n- **Angle of Attack at Stall:** ~23 degrees\n\n### **Factors Influencing These Values**\n\nIt's important to note that these figures are approximate and can vary based on several factors, including:\n\n- **Aircraft Weight:** Heavier weights can increase stall speed.\n- **Altitude and Air Density:** Higher altitudes with thinner air can affect both stall speed and AOA.\n- **Configuration:** Flaps, landing gear position, and other control surfaces can influence stall characteristics.\n- **Environmental Conditions:** Atmospheric conditions like temperature and wind can also play a role.\n\nFor precise operational data, especially for pilot training or technical purposes, referring to official F-14 flight manuals or manufacturer specifications is recommended.",
